    <div class="container content-container">
      <h2>Parent Visa: Document Checklist</h2>
      <p>Sponsoring parents has a higher salary requirement and specific documentation needs. This visa type proves the parent-child relationship in reverse — your birth certificate shows you are their child.</p>

      <h3>Salary Requirement</h3>
      <p>To sponsor parents, the typical minimum salary is AED 20,000 per month (or AED 15,000 plus employer-provided accommodation). This is significantly higher than the spouse visa threshold. Requirements may vary by emirate.</p>

      <h3>Documents That Need Translation and Attestation</h3>
      <ul class="content-list">
        <li><strong><a href="/personal/vital-records/birth/">Your birth certificate</a></strong> — This proves the parent-child relationship. Must be attested from the country where it was issued and MOJ-translated.</li>
        <li><strong>Parent's passport copy</strong> — Identification. If not in English or Arabic, the bio-data page needs translation.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Documents That Need Translation Only</h3>
      <ul class="content-list">
        <li><strong><a href="/personal/immigration/bank/">Bank statements</a></strong> — Last 3-6 months showing sufficient funds. MOJ translation required.</li>
        <li><strong>Salary certificate</strong> — From your UAE employer. Translation required if in a foreign language.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Other Required Documents</h3>
      <ul class="content-list">
        <li><strong>Your passport and Emirates ID copies</strong> — No translation needed.</li>
        <li><strong>Tenancy contract</strong> — Proving adequate accommodation. Arabic Ejari does not need translation.</li>
        <li><strong>Health insurance for the parent</strong> — Must be arranged before visa stamping.</li>
        <li><strong>Medical fitness certificate</strong> — Parent takes this test after arrival in UAE.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Attestation Chains -->
  <section class="section bg-white">
    <div class="container content-container">
      <h2>Attestation Chains for Family Documents</h2>
      <p>Marriage and birth certificates must be authenticated before translation. The <a href="/services/attestation/">attestation process</a> depends on where the document was issued.</p>

      <h3>Hague Convention Countries (Apostille Route)</h3>
      <p>Countries with Hague membership use the simplified apostille system. The apostille replaces the embassy attestation chain.</p>
      <ul class="content-list">
        <li><strong>India</strong> — MEA apostille. Some states require SDM attestation before MEA. Marriage certificates must be from a registered marriage.</li>
        <li><strong>United Kingdom</strong> — FCDO apostille. Birth and marriage certificates from the General Register Office are eligible.</li>
        <li><strong>United States</strong> — State-level apostille for state-issued documents. Processing varies by state.</li>
        <li><strong>Canada</strong> — GAC apostille (member since January 2024). Provincial vital records offices issue the certificates.</li>
        <li><strong>Philippines</strong> — DFA apostille. PSA-issued birth and marriage certificates on security paper.</li>
        <li><strong>Bangladesh</strong> — Apostille available since March 2025. Older documents may need the traditional chain.</li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong>Route:</strong> Home country attestation (if needed) → Apostille → UAE MOFA → MOJ translation</p>

      <h3>Non-Hague Countries (Full Attestation Chain)</h3>
      <p>Countries outside the Hague Convention require the traditional, longer process.</p>
      <ul class="content-list">
        <li><strong>Pakistan</strong> — Home MOFA → UAE Embassy in Islamabad or Karachi → UAE MOFA → MOJ translation</li>
        <li><strong>Egypt, Jordan, Syria, Lebanon</strong> — Similar embassy chain through the respective UAE Embassy</li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong>Route:</strong> Home country MOFA → UAE Embassy in home country → UAE MOFA → MOJ translation</p>

      <div class="info-callout warning">
        <i class="fas fa-exclamation-triangle"></i>
        <div>
          <strong>UAE is NOT a Hague Convention Member</strong>
          <p>The UAE has not joined the Hague Convention. This means UAE-issued documents (like a UAE marriage certificate for a couple married in the UAE) cannot use the apostille system when going abroad. For family visa purposes, what matters is the Hague status of the country that issued your document.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Document Validity -->
  <section class="section bg-light">
    <div class="container content-container">
      <h2>Document Validity Periods</h2>
      <p>Not all documents last forever. GDRFA has specific expectations about document freshness.</p>

      <div class="validity-grid">
        <div class="validity-card">
          <h3>No Expiry</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><a href="/personal/vital-records/marriage/">Marriage certificate</a> — permanent</li>
            <li><a href="/personal/vital-records/birth/">Birth certificate</a> — permanent</li>
            <li>MOJ translation — does not expire</li>
            <li>Attestation stamps — do not expire</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="validity-card time-sensitive">
          <h3>Time-Sensitive</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><a href="/personal/immigration/pcc/">Police clearance</a> — 3-6 months from issue</li>
            <li><a href="/personal/immigration/bank/">Bank statements</a> — within last 3 months</li>
            <li>Salary certificate — within last month</li>
            <li>Medical fitness — valid per GDRFA guidelines</li>
            <li>Health insurance — must be active at stamping</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>Plan your timeline around the time-sensitive documents. Get permanent documents (marriage, birth) attested and translated first. Order time-sensitive documents (PCC, bank statements) closer to your GDRFA submission date.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Common Rejections -->
  <section class="section bg-white">
    <div class="container content-container">
      <h2>Common Family Visa Rejection Reasons</h2>
      <p>GDRFA family visa rejections typically fall into document problems or eligibility issues. Document problems are preventable. For more details, read our <a href="/blog/gdrfa-visa-document-problems/">article on GDRFA document problems</a>.</p>

      <div class="rejection-list">
        <div class="rejection-item">
          <h3><i class="fas fa-times-circle"></i> Name Mismatch Between Documents</h3>
          <p>The spouse's name on the marriage certificate must match the passport exactly. "Fatima" vs "Fatimah," "Ahmad" vs "Ahmed" — even single-letter differences cause rejection. We cross-reference all names against passports before issuing translation.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="rejection-item">
          <h3><i class="fas fa-times-circle"></i> Missing Attestation Step</h3>
          <p>The attestation chain must be complete. A marriage certificate with an apostille but no MOFA stamp will be rejected. A birth certificate with home country attestation but no UAE Embassy stamp (non-Hague) will be sent back. Every link in the chain matters.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="rejection-item">
          <h3><i class="fas fa-times-circle"></i> Expired Police Clearance Certificate</h3>
          <p>PCCs have a limited validity window. If GDRFA processing takes longer than expected and your PCC expires during that time, the entire application may be returned. Order the PCC at the right time — not too early, not too late.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="rejection-item">
          <h3><i class="fas fa-times-circle"></i> Wrong Translation Type</h3>
          <p>Certified translation (agency stamp only) instead of MOJ translation (judiciary seal) is an automatic rejection. GDRFA requires the MOJ seal on all foreign-language documents. Read our <a href="/resources/moj-vs-certified/">comparison of MOJ vs certified translation</a>.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="rejection-item">
          <h3><i class="fas fa-times-circle"></i> Insufficient Salary Proof</h3>
          <p>If your salary certificate or bank statements do not meet the minimum threshold, the application is rejected. This is an eligibility issue, not a document issue. However, bank statement translation errors (wrong figures) can also trigger this rejection.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="rejection-item">
          <h3><i class="fas fa-times-circle"></i> Unregistered Marriage</h3>
          <p>Religious ceremonies without legal registration are not recognized. A mosque or temple marriage must be legally registered with the civil authority of the issuing country. GDRFA requires the government-registered marriage certificate, not a religious one.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="rejection-item">
          <h3><i class="fas fa-times-circle"></i> Incomplete Translation</h3>
          <p>All text on the original must appear in the Arabic translation. Stamps, seals, handwritten notes, and endorsements cannot be omitted. An incomplete translation is grounds for rejection. We translate every visible element on the document.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Step-by-Step Process -->
  <section class="section bg-light">
    <div class="container content-container">
      <h2>Step-by-Step: Preparing Family Visa Documents</h2>
      <p>Follow this order. Each step depends on the previous one being complete.</p>

      <div class="process-steps">
        <div class="step">
          <div class="step-number">1</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <h3>Confirm Eligibility</h3>
            <p>Check that your salary, accommodation, and job category meet GDRFA sponsorship requirements. Verify which documents are needed for your specific visa type (spouse, child, parent). Contact GDRFA or check the ICA Smart Services portal for current requirements.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="step">
          <div class="step-number">2</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <h3>Gather and Attest Documents</h3>
            <p>Collect original <a href="/personal/vital-records/marriage/">marriage certificates</a>, <a href="/personal/vital-records/birth/">birth certificates</a>, and any other required documents. Complete <a href="/services/attestation/">attestation</a> in the issuing country (apostille for Hague members, full chain for others). Then get UAE MOFA attestation.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="step">
          <div class="step-number">3</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <h3>Get MOJ Arabic Translation</h3>
            <p>Send all attested documents to us via WhatsApp (+971 50 862 0217). We verify the attestation chain is complete, translate each document with the MOJ seal, and deliver within 1 hour for standard documents. We also cross-check names against passports.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="step">
          <div class="step-number">4</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <h3>Submit to GDRFA and Complete Remaining Steps</h3>
            <p>Submit the complete package to GDRFA (online through the GDRFA app or at a service centre). After entry permit issuance, your family member arrives in the UAE, completes the medical fitness test, obtains health insurance, and gets the visa stamped.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Tips by Relationship -->
  <section class="section bg-white">
    <div class="container content-container">
      <h2>Practical Tips by Visa Type</h2>

      <h3>Spouse Visa Tips</h3>
      <ul class="content-list">
        <li>Get the <a href="/personal/vital-records/marriage/">marriage certificate</a> attested before your spouse travels. This avoids delays after arrival.</li>
        <li>If you married in the UAE, the UAE marriage certificate is already in Arabic. No translation needed — only MOFA attestation if used for another government entity.</li>
        <li>Name changes after marriage must be reflected in the passport. A marriage certificate showing a maiden name with a passport showing a married name will cause issues.</li>
        <li>For previously divorced sponsors: a <a href="/personal/vital-records/divorce/">divorce decree</a> from the previous marriage may be required. Check with GDRFA.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Children Visa Tips</h3>
      <ul class="content-list">
        <li>Children born in the UAE already have Arabic birth certificates. Foreign birth certificate translation is needed only for children born outside the UAE.</li>
        <li>For adopted children, the adoption order needs full attestation and translation. The process may take longer due to additional verification.</li>
        <li>Stepchildren require the marriage certificate to the current spouse plus the child's birth certificate showing the biological parent.</li>
        <li>Plan translations for all children at once. Submitting as a batch is more efficient than one at a time.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Parent Visa Tips</h3>
      <ul class="content-list">
        <li>The salary threshold is high (AED 15,000-20,000). Confirm current requirements before beginning the document process.</li>
        <li>Your <a href="/personal/vital-records/birth/">birth certificate</a> is the key document — it proves the parent-child relationship.</li>
        <li>Health insurance for parents must be arranged before visa stamping. Some insurance providers have age restrictions.</li>
        <li>Parent visas are typically issued for 1 year and are renewable. Keep all original documents for renewal.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

